<font color="#FF0000">THE WALL</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jul 14 22:57:35 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Memorial Day 1997 was the 5th year I visited the wall to see  my father's name there.  He was a paratrooper, 1/12 Cavalry,  killed in An Khe, May 21, 1966.   I never knew him as my mother was pregnant when he died.  It took me a long time to go there after my first visit in the late 80's.  I swore I would never go back again.  The pain felt not only for the loss of my father but also for the loss of so many men and women on that wall was overwhelming.  <br><br>
When I was in D.C. the first time, I posted my fathers name on a list of people looking for friends or relatives of Veterans (Friends of the Vietnam Memorial) expecting to find his family whom I never knew.   In 1992 I received a call from a man who was with my father when he was killed.  His thoughtfulness and caring persuaded me to return to D.C.  This time I had a friend to help me understand the pain.  <br><br>
We met the first time on Veteran's Day 1992.  He was a Godsend for me.  He taught me things about my father that my mother could not have known during that time.  He made me proud of my father and proud of the men who served with him before, during and after he was there.  I have been back every year since on Memorial Day weekend  for a reunion of sorts which consists of meeting with Frank and his wife and others we have collected along the way.  <br><br>
Every year we visit my father on the Wall, Daniel G. Post, Jr., Panel 7E, Line 98.  We also visit his grave in Arlington where we leave flowers and prayers hoping he can hear me when I tell him I am so proud to be his daughter and wonder if he would have been proud of me too.   I Love My Dad!<br><br>
Sometimes,  I wonder who suffers more.....the survivors or the ones that did not make it.  The guilt many surviving Veterans carry is quite visible and heartwrenching.  My heart goes out to you all.  From someone who is surviving too I would say to those harboring such guilt  that they should not feel guilty for living no more than I do not feel guilty that my father died.  I am and will remain PROUD of my father and those who served with him.  <br><br>
GOD BLESS YOU ALL.<br><br>
 
<p><code>-- DAWNEE@AOL.COM  (Dawn R. Post) </code><p>


